comments.message:
I would prefer we keep snippets inside of ./snippets/api.json so that we can keep it separate from the typescript logic and reduce clutter. I scanned a couple of vscode extension guides and thats also the convention they use. 

What do you think about that Tung?

Hi Lukasz,

Because we use data in the snippets .json files for the hover feature, the snippets .json files need to be imported in hover.ts. Thus, VSCode will considers this files as the extension's source code, this files must be placed in src folder. So I have to replace them into src folder. If I don't do it, VSCode will raise error when building extension.

I think this implement works OK and the snippets files still are managed in only one folder. Please let me know if you have a better idea for it.

In current, we have two error formats that beginning with two following string:
- "[ERROR (root level)] " with a white space at the ending.
- "** ERROR:\n" with a new line symbol at the ending

Updated snippets in the following improvement:
-Prefix is unique between the snippets. It describes to the snippet's function that the user usually uses to call it. It also should be as simple as possible
-All parameter in the snippet should not be hard code. We will give the default value and let the user change it (using tab parameter)

I like that we are now providing snippets for the subsections found in the different Legato definition/api files.   However, I think that the description fields for our snippets are too short.  We need to provide more description to make the snippets more helpful to the user.  

Now, rather than trying to come up with our own descriptions for each of the sections, I think we should try to copy/re-use what is already available on legato.io.  Legato.io documents nicely all the subsections for each file types covered by our snippets.  I have provided some examples on how this might be done.

comments.message:
Instead of hard coding the name and calling it a hello world snippet, we should allow the user to choose the name.

So, here I'm making the base name a tab parameter and I'm giving it the default value of the file name that the user is entering the snippet in.

One other thing we should be doing is adding some extra spacing to multi section snippets like this.  So between the separate sub-groups I added an empty line:  "",


"new_adef": {
      "description": "Generate new ADEF contents.",
      "prefix": [ "new_adef" ],

      "body": [
        "executables:",
        "{",
        "\t${0:${TM_FILENAME_BASE}}Executable = ( ${0:${TM_FILENAME_BASE}}Component )",
        "}",
        "",
        "processes:",
        "{",
        "\tenvVars:",
        "\t{",
        "\t\tLE_LOG_LEVEL = DEBUG",
        "\t}",
        "",
        "\trun:",
        "\t{",
        "\t\t( ${0:${TM_FILENAME_BASE}}Executable )",
        "\t}",
        "}",
        ""
      ]
    }

These are not good prefixes.  It should be something specific to the snipit, not a grab bag of tags.

"New Read Transaction" would be better.

Here again.  This is generating a whole function, when we just want a few lines of code.

We're generating code as someone to use it, not to act as a complete sample.

This also needs to be made more succinct.  This also may not be good as a snippet.

snippets should only be there to automate common tasks.  The idea is that they speed up things the programmer does all the time.

Looping with Legato iterators.  Would be an example of this.

Just ripping examples out of the API guides are not a good way to go.  This isn't a copy and paste situation.

These snippets need to be rethought and possibly removed.

Really, you need to go through and re-review all of these.

Snippets are not example code, they are a shorthand for working code which is very different.

Using the sample code isn't a bad way to start, but it needs to be reworked into something that the user can actually use.  The prefixes on the snippet needs to be something close to what the user will actually type, don't treat it like a grab bag of hash tags.  They also really need to be unique, don't share these prefixes between the snippets.

For example (taken from https://docs.legato.io/latest/defFilesAdef.html#defFilesAdef_executables):

"Lists executables to be constructed and moved to the bin directory inside the app."

For example (https://docs.legato.io/latest/defFilesAdef.html#defFilesAdef_bindings):

"Allow client-side IPC API interfaces (listed in the requires sections of Component.cdef files) to be bound to server-side interfaces (listed in the provides sections of Component.cdef files)."

For example (taken from https://docs.legato.io/latest/defFiles.html#defFilesOverview_sdef):

"Defines a system of one or more applications that can be deployed to target devices in the field."

For example (taken from https://docs.legato.io/latest/defFilesSdef.html):

"Used to find the .api files referenced in your system, your applications, and the components that make up your applications."

For example (taken from https://docs.legato.io/latest/defFilesSdef.html):

"Used when specifying apps in your .sdef's apps: section. Instead of having to specify a full path to your applications, you can specify locations for where they should be found."
Even though this is how it is written in our Legato.io docs, I think we should say "Specify", instead of "Allow".

Can you please double check the list of commands available in the .adef file.   Not sure it supports "provides".

Also, I see that there are a number of other commands available, such as "cpuShare", "sandboxed", "start", maxThreads", "watchdogAction", etc., that would be worth including in our snippets.

The section "provides" still is used in .adef source file, such as: legato-src/legato/build/localhost/apps/test/framework/mk/bin-app/build-app/hello/hello.adef. I think it is still being supported as it is mentioned on adef document. 
I have added more snippets for adef and mdef. I also modify the description of snippets as your comment
In keeping with the other snippets, you may want to make this "Declare" instead.
I suggest replacing "Provide a way to specify" with "Specify" instead.
Replace "List all module parameters" with "Specify module parameters" instead.

Let's simplify this.

"Add files and directories that will be bundled with the kernel module and copied from the build host to the target."
Replace "Use to find the .api files" with "Specify the search path for .api files".
Replace "Use when specifying apps in" with "Specify the search path for apps declared in"
Replace "Use to add the paths" with "Specify the search path".

This one is a bit clumsy.  I think we should replace the entire things, 

"Specify the search path for modules declared in your .sdef's kernelModules: section.  Instead of having to specify a full path to your kernel modules, you can specify locations for where they should be found."
Replace "To make a command-line tool available" with "Specify command-line tools that will be available"
Please remove this one.  It belongs to an experimental feature (RPC), and shouldn't be shown right now.
That seem "assets" is no longer supported in cdef file. Do we still need to add it to snippets list?

I think we should include the snippets for the sub-commands under the apps.   You have done this in other cases, such as kernelModules under the requires sections of the .mdef.   We should try to be consistent with this across the different definition files.
I think we should also include externalWatchdogKick.

Hi Tung, please re-word this differently.  Perhaps,

"Specify the maximum timeout length (in milliseconds) the app can be stopped. If the app is stopped longer than the timeout given in maxWatchdogTimeout, the system will try to recover itself and may reboot the target."
No, this is not what I was suggesting.  I was really just talking about "maxPriority", and perhaps "preloaded", if it makes sense.

comments.message: True when Explorer is a file system resource. False when Explorer is an empty folder. When Explorer contains an empty folder, leaf view container should be shown in order to create a new profile on it.

The goal here is for the package view to work when there is no folder, not to hide it.

These views should be visible and populated.

In keeping with my comment from the Jira ticket, I think it is cleaning and clearer if we make the pop-up notification box simply acted as a warning box, telling the user "There is no workspace folder. Please open a workspace folder first.".

Instead of having an "Open Folder" button, it would only provide an "OK" button, which only acts to close the notification box.   The onus of opening a workspace falls back onto the user.
Please keep line lengths under 80 characters.

comments.message:
It would be good to consider the TARGET_SSH_PORT option to define the SSH port.
Depending on how we are connecting to the target, assuming that we can reach it on port 22 is not the best.

When running a virtual platform (virt, wp76, ar ...), qemu exports the port 22 on some other port (10022 for instance), so that parameter could be useful.
Bertrand, is the variable TARGET_SSH_PORT exported by leaf package if the packages aims qemu target?
Not at the moment. There is no qemu leaf package for now, but even then it would be more something dynamic with a default to 22.

I spoke about it with Nicolas, the problem is we have many call to ssh and if we use an alternative port here, we should also change all other ssh calls.
We should trace this in a separate ticket, because this will require a not trivial development.
Sure, and as you can see below the fact that we have so many different calls to SSH instead of centralized function is a problem too, as that duplication should IMHO not exist.
Would have been nice to reuse getRemoteShellCmd() it seems.

command -v ccze is usually better than which.

command -v is provided by the shell (built-in) while which needs to be installed.
Jokes on us, that doesn't work anymore as of Release 12 :(

comments.message: Just a TS beginner dev remark, this file looks like generated, shouldn't it be ignored by git?

the package-lock.json file specify the exact version of each package. The package.json only specify max and min versions.
So even if it's generated, you may want to use custom options in your 'npm install' command or your 'npm audit fix' command to ensure that your commit work.

Create Legato Extension API

Remove singleton pattern everywhere
Create an Extension class that will handle managers instances and external access
Reuse new special promises created for API access into bridge, process and sheduler
Let it possible to use different cwd on each ProcessLauncher call
Remove unused properties from leaf task definition
Fix event listener not disposed/unregistered
Improve ioManager API to add process/shell selection
Fix remove package from profile not working (&& must be executed in a shell)
Use TaskScope instead of WorkspaceFolder when creating tasks
Implement workaround for issue https://github.com/Microsoft/vscode/issues/68486

comments.message: Leaf packages are embedded official images to be flashed, so we shouldn't exclude leaf-data when browsing cwe/spk files

User partition reset should be "protected" with a confirmation popup message:
"This will restore the device file system by erasing all user files" + OK/Cancel buttons
We should use a popup window instead (maybe more consistent with other workflows)

Well, we're getting too much files now :)
If possible, let's exclude what's not in **/leaf-data/current.

I also wonder if we couldn't display files as
"basename (workspace_relative_dirname)" in the list...
Since at the moment filenames are truncated, and it's not possible to scroll horizontally, and there is no tooltip

this is *excluding* leaf-data/current, while we may want to exclude everything else...

Maybe we need another construction, with 2 findFiles call:
* one on the global workspace, excluding leaf-data
* one on the folder pointed by $(echo ${LEGATO_TARGET} | tr 'a-z' 'A-R')_DEVICE_IMAGES variable
Should be "leaf-data/current/**/*.{cwe,spk}", otherwise profile files are not found

comments.message: Why it does not work with https ? It seems to work on my navigator.

have you recently made a npm install ? btw, it's not my own update.

package.json updated to switch the target platform on the stable nodejs version and npm install has restored https :-/

https://npm.community/t/npm-install-downgrading-resolved-packages-from-https-to-http-registry-in-package-lock-json/1818/14
You don't need to pass this argument, it's already available in the method scope.
Please extract this to a separate async method.

A getter should not change the state of the object.
You have to separate the refreshing from the caching.

If env is provided, the unique use content of this method is to return the value of a properties. Do we really need it ?
Get an envar giving the env var or not is bit confusing.
This argument is useless since we already have access to this property in this scope.
Please extract this to a separate async method named onLeafFileChange
turned into a separate const to have closure on external fsWait
Please extract this to an async method named onEnvChanged
Please extract this to an async method named onEnvChanged
Please extract this to an async method named onEnvChanged
because no need to launch a big shell like zsh (if it's the one defined by the user) for remote. But you're right, I think it should be vscode plugin setting...

Not generating an "envChanged" event on a profile switch is an issue.
Typically, if different profiles have different DEST_IPs, the status bar won't be updated.

Maybe the envChanged event should be always emitted; and maybe we don't need a profileChanged event...
